{"author":{"id":"4bb6c1767e50694cfde61856db22bf137d1651e8a0b5ca858c486db3dd02f280"},"ops":[{"type":3,"timestamp":1778541386,"nonce":"N4MmUMF3/mLf52omT5HtotwqGKY=","message":"## New lesson — `--ports` flag must be explicit on `pod create`\n\n**Symptom**: a freshly-created `runpodctl pod create` (4090 secure cloud, default flags) returns `ports: null`. The pod boots but has no public TCP. `runpodctl pod get` reports `ssh.error: \"pod not ready\"` and `uptimeSeconds: 0` indefinitely (the field never updates without exposed ports). SSH attempts via the RunPod proxy (`ssh.runpod.io`) fail with \"Permission denied (publickey)\" because the proxy uses account-level keys, not the `PUBLIC_KEY` env injected at pod creation.\n\n**Root cause**: `runpodctl pod create` defaults `--ports` to nothing exposed. The runbook in CLAUDE.md §4a does not include this flag in its example. Older pods (and the prior 5090 we re-used in this session) had `[\"22/tcp\", \"8080/http\"]` exposed — likely from a previous runpodctl default that has since changed, or from an explicit flag in an earlier version of the runbook.\n\n**Fix**: always pass `--ports \"22/tcp,8080/http\"` to `pod create`. Direct TCP SSH then works with the existing `RunPod-Key-Go` injected via `PUBLIC_KEY` env.\n\n**Adjacent finding**: `uptimeSeconds` from `runpodctl pod get` is NOT a reliable \"pod alive\" signal when ports are not exposed. It stays at `0` for hours on a fully-running container. The reliable signal is \"can I actually SSH in?\" — perform a functional SSH test (not a uptime poll).\n\n**Add to CLAUDE.md §4a**:\n\n```\nrunpodctl pod create \\\n  --image \"runpod/pytorch:1.0.3-cu1281-torch290-ubuntu2204\" \\\n  --gpu-id \"NVIDIA GeForce RTX 4090\" \\\n  --cloud-type SECURE \\\n  --container-disk-in-gb 30 \\\n  --volume-in-gb 30 \\\n  --ports \"22/tcp,8080/http\"   # ← REQUIRED for direct TCP SSH; default is no ports\n```\n\nPlus a note: \"If `--ports` is omitted, the pod boots without public TCP; SSH via the proxy works only if the account-registered key matches what `~/.runpod/ssh/RunPod-Key-Go` is. The runpodctl `uptimeSeconds` field stays 0 indefinitely without exposed ports — do not use it as a liveness signal.\"\n\nSurfaced this session (2026-05-11) after burning ~$0.34 on two stuck pods that were actually alive but not SSH-reachable. Filed for inclusion in the next CLAUDE.md update cycle.","files":null}]}